WEBVTT

00:01.898 --> 00:05.177
[mechanical sounds]

00:05.212 --> 00:07.076
- Maybe
you know him.

00:07.110 --> 00:08.836
I hope you know him
from such excellent shows as

00:08.870 --> 00:11.425
"United Shades of America,"

00:11.459 --> 00:16.050
host, writer, comedian,
W. Kamau Bell.

00:16.085 --> 00:17.845
[upbeat music]

00:17.879 --> 00:20.399
I bumped into him in
the CNN "C" room recently

00:20.434 --> 00:22.263
fondling his Emmy,
and I asked him,

00:22.298 --> 00:24.541
"Kamau, if you could go
anywhere on Earth

00:24.576 --> 00:26.854
"for, like, a mash-up episode
of my show and yours,

00:26.888 --> 00:28.821
where would
that be?"

00:28.856 --> 00:30.064
He said Kenya.

00:30.099 --> 00:32.584
- [laughs]

00:32.618 --> 00:35.207
- So here we are,

00:35.242 --> 00:38.072
"United Shades Unknown"
or "Parts United."

00:38.107 --> 00:40.178
Scratch that.
That--that doesn't sound good.

00:40.212 --> 00:42.663
"America's Shadiest Parts."

00:42.697 --> 00:44.147
No, no,
that doesn't work either.

00:44.182 --> 00:46.494
"Unknown Shades of"...

00:46.529 --> 00:48.358
[upbeat rock music]

00:48.393 --> 00:50.257
both: ♪ I took a walk
through this ♪

00:50.291 --> 00:53.398
♪ Beautiful world

00:53.432 --> 00:58.541
♪ Felt the cool rain
on my shoulder ♪

00:58.575 --> 01:02.200
♪ Found something good
in this ♪

01:02.234 --> 01:04.719
♪ Beautiful world

01:04.754 --> 01:10.553
♪ I felt the rain
getting colder ♪

01:10.587 --> 01:14.108
- ♪ La, la
- ♪ Sha la, la, la, la

01:14.143 --> 01:15.834
♪ Sha la, la, la, la

01:15.868 --> 01:20.114
- ♪ Sha la, la, la
- Sha la, la, la, la ♪

01:20.149 --> 01:24.877
♪ Sha la, la, la, la, la

01:27.777 --> 01:32.195
[upbeat music]

01:32.230 --> 01:35.371
♪

01:35.405 --> 01:37.614
- First time
on this continent.

01:37.649 --> 01:39.237
- Yes.
[laughs]

01:39.271 --> 01:40.893
- I'm gonna be teasing you
relentlessly about this,

01:40.928 --> 01:41.929
by the way.
- That's fine.

01:41.963 --> 01:43.275
Please, please,
please, yeah.

01:43.310 --> 01:45.450
As an African-American,

01:45.484 --> 01:47.693
there's a lot of talk about
going back to this thing

01:47.728 --> 01:49.695
of the "motherland."

01:49.730 --> 01:53.354
- And that--it--seriously
radicalizing experience

01:53.389 --> 01:56.357
for African-American comics
who come here before.

01:56.392 --> 01:57.841
- Yes. Yeah, yeah, yeah.
- Life changing.

01:57.876 --> 01:58.842
So we shall see.

01:58.877 --> 02:02.708
♪

02:02.743 --> 02:05.194
- I mean, even walking
through the streets,

02:05.228 --> 02:06.333
like, I have this feeling
of, like,

02:06.367 --> 02:08.956
when I moved from Chicago
to Oakland.

02:08.990 --> 02:11.407
You know, you hear about Oakland
being this black city...

02:11.441 --> 02:12.925
- Uh-huh.
- And you get there

02:12.960 --> 02:14.410
and it's like,
I got these black people here

02:14.444 --> 02:16.239
but it's not like--
- Uh-huh.

02:16.274 --> 02:17.240
- This is what I imagined
Oakland was gonna be like.

02:17.275 --> 02:19.208
- [laughs]

02:19.242 --> 02:21.382
- This is like--this feels like
this is black, you know?

02:21.417 --> 02:24.903
[upbeat music]

02:24.937 --> 02:26.215
- [speaking native language]

02:26.249 --> 02:29.321
♪

02:29.356 --> 02:32.911
- Nairobi means "cool water"
in Maasai.

02:32.945 --> 02:35.431
It's the capital of Kenya with
6.5 million people

02:35.465 --> 02:37.502
living in
the metro area.

02:37.536 --> 02:40.953
♪

02:40.988 --> 02:42.748
It grew up around
a British railroad depot

02:42.783 --> 02:44.681
during
the colonial era,

02:44.716 --> 02:47.753
halfway between other
British interests in Uganda

02:47.788 --> 02:49.272
and the coastal port
of Mombasa.

02:49.307 --> 02:52.517
- [singing in foreign language]

02:52.551 --> 02:55.934
♪

02:55.968 --> 02:59.869
- I will admit to a weird,
frankly unlovely sense

02:59.903 --> 03:01.733
of been here,
done that.

03:01.767 --> 03:03.562
It's not a good look for me,
I know,

03:03.597 --> 03:05.564
but there's a mischievous
curiosity tucked away

03:05.599 --> 03:07.808
in some poisonous part of
my brain

03:07.842 --> 03:10.397
that's dying to see
how Kamau handles the heat,

03:10.431 --> 03:12.330
the spice,
the crowds,

03:12.364 --> 03:15.540
the overwhelming rush of
a whole new world,

03:15.574 --> 03:17.887
because that's what it is
first time.

03:17.921 --> 03:19.889
This
ain't Berkeley.

03:19.923 --> 03:22.512
[sirens wail]

03:22.547 --> 03:23.272
- Wah!

03:23.306 --> 03:25.791
[upbeat music]

03:25.826 --> 03:28.242
♪

03:29.657 --> 03:30.831
- I'm already happy.
- I'm pretty happy

03:30.865 --> 03:35.249
because I've seen this scene
so many times on your show.

03:35.284 --> 03:36.906
I finally get to
be in this scene of

03:36.940 --> 03:38.563
this is
gonna be good.

03:38.597 --> 03:40.254
- I mean,
you have a Kenyan name.

03:40.289 --> 03:44.258
- Yes. My parents met in
East Palo Alto, California.

03:46.018 --> 03:48.366
You know, this is like
the late '60s,

03:48.400 --> 03:49.608
starting to be
the early '70s,

03:49.643 --> 03:51.403
so post the Civil Rights
movement

03:51.438 --> 03:52.956
but that point where black
people were starting to, like,

03:52.991 --> 03:54.579
really like want a connection
to the motherland.

03:54.613 --> 03:59.031
And in East Palo Alto,
there was this push

03:59.066 --> 04:01.517
towards
naming it Nairobi,

04:01.551 --> 04:03.415
Nairobi, California.

04:03.450 --> 04:05.555
Back then, people were like, we need to be associated with,

04:05.590 --> 04:07.350
like, an example of African
culture that is winning.

04:07.385 --> 04:09.559
At that point, Kenya was
looked at as being winning

04:09.594 --> 04:11.596
'cause they had just
kicked out the Brits,

04:11.630 --> 04:13.632
and there was all this sort of like, you know,

04:13.667 --> 04:15.462
we need to start a whole new
culture and a new government.

04:15.496 --> 04:17.567
They started, like,
a community college

04:17.602 --> 04:18.948
that's in people's houses
and in basements

04:18.982 --> 04:20.708
and in
storefronts.

04:20.743 --> 04:22.883
And I was the first baby born to
one of the heads of the council

04:22.917 --> 04:24.747
apparently,

04:24.781 --> 04:26.542
and apparently, there was,
like, a whole ceremony,

04:26.576 --> 04:28.613
lasted eight days
and, you know, "Ahh."

04:28.647 --> 04:30.580
Like, you know, I picture it
like "The Lion King."

04:30.615 --> 04:32.030
I don't know,
there's no pictures.

04:32.064 --> 04:34.998
[upbeat music]

04:35.033 --> 04:39.900
♪

04:39.934 --> 04:42.385
- Tilapia from
Lake Naivasha

04:42.420 --> 04:44.732
fried, then cooked with
tomato and spices.

04:44.767 --> 04:46.458
Served up right
on the bone

04:46.493 --> 04:50.566
with
an ice-cold Tusker.

04:50.600 --> 04:53.396
And yet,
a proud Kenyan name.

04:53.431 --> 04:57.055
Given your background,
why so long? Why--

04:57.089 --> 04:59.437
- [laughs]
- What took you so long, man?

04:59.471 --> 05:01.059
- I was waiting for
an invitation,

05:01.093 --> 05:03.130
the right invitation.
- I mean, what--what--

05:03.164 --> 05:05.615
was there any concern
you would be disappointed?

05:05.650 --> 05:08.722
- I think as a black American,
I'm still wrestling

05:08.756 --> 05:10.724
with my African-American
identity sometimes,

05:10.758 --> 05:12.484
and I'm still wondering, am
I doing right by this culture

05:12.519 --> 05:14.831
and does this culture think
I'm doing right by them?

05:14.866 --> 05:16.350
That's why I don't want
to walk around like,

05:16.385 --> 05:18.076
"I'm home!"
[laughs]

05:18.110 --> 05:20.906
[dramatic music]

05:20.941 --> 05:22.598
I also think that, like,
a lot of times blacks in America

05:22.632 --> 05:24.462
heavily struggle with that
aspect of identity.

05:24.496 --> 05:26.084
What does it mean to be
black in America?

05:26.118 --> 05:28.569
I'm like, I fought hard
to claim this identity.

05:28.604 --> 05:30.399
It's exhausting,
you know.

05:30.433 --> 05:32.539
Am I ready to start with
a new one? I don't know yet.

05:32.573 --> 05:34.126
- Well, we'll see in a--
we'll see in a week

05:34.161 --> 05:35.404
when you head back.

05:35.438 --> 05:37.371
- Exactly, yeah.
[laughs]

05:37.406 --> 05:41.099
[soft percussive music]

05:41.133 --> 05:42.134
- Shit
runs deep here.

05:42.169 --> 05:44.758
Meaning,
best scientists can tell,

05:44.792 --> 05:48.451
it all started for us
in this neighborhood.

05:48.486 --> 05:51.074
Tribes of
hunter-gatherers,

05:51.109 --> 05:53.076
the Bantu
and Nilotic peoples,

05:53.111 --> 05:54.733
Arab and Persian
traders,

05:54.768 --> 05:58.081
the Portuguese merchants,
the Omani

05:58.116 --> 05:59.911
all left
their mark.

05:59.945 --> 06:01.706
♪

06:01.740 --> 06:05.434
But the British Empire's hold
from 1895 to 1964

06:05.468 --> 06:08.126
is perhaps
most deeply felt.

06:08.160 --> 06:11.198
The British system
of education,

06:11.232 --> 06:13.442
governance, justice,
along with,

06:13.476 --> 06:15.582
to a certain extent,
its values

06:15.616 --> 06:17.411
were imposed on
a native people

06:17.446 --> 06:18.930
and laid,
for better and worse,

06:18.964 --> 06:21.829
much of the foundation for
modern Kenya.

06:21.864 --> 06:24.591
It did abolish slavery,
for instance.

06:24.625 --> 06:26.558
It did build
a modern infrastructure.

06:26.593 --> 06:29.423
It was also completely
and fundamentally

06:29.458 --> 06:31.460
exploitative,
often violent,

06:31.494 --> 06:33.082
and well,
racist,

06:33.116 --> 06:35.015
favoring white settlers,
land owners,

06:35.049 --> 06:38.950
and foreign entrepreneurs
in every possible way.

06:38.984 --> 06:41.884
Kenya existed to make
white people from far away

06:41.918 --> 06:44.093
rich.

06:44.127 --> 06:47.890
♪

06:47.924 --> 06:51.583
But in 1963 Kenya won
its independence

06:51.618 --> 06:52.791
and elected
its first president,

06:52.826 --> 06:54.552
Jomo Kenyatta.

06:54.586 --> 06:56.933
And since that time,
has fought an uphill battle

06:56.968 --> 06:59.936
to shake the last vestiges
of colonial rule

06:59.971 --> 07:02.732
while hanging onto
what worked.

07:02.767 --> 07:06.080
♪

07:06.115 --> 07:08.117
Things are, by most accounts,
going well.

07:08.151 --> 07:11.223
[upbeat music]

07:11.258 --> 07:13.950
Today's Kenya is
phenomenally beautiful.

07:15.883 --> 07:17.954
There is a growing
middle class,

07:17.989 --> 07:19.162
a highly rated
educational system,

07:19.197 --> 07:21.613
and an enthusiastic

07:21.648 --> 07:23.270
and multilingual
professional sector,

07:23.304 --> 07:27.101
which is to say this is
decidedly not a shithole.

07:27.136 --> 07:28.931
There are
poor people here

07:28.965 --> 07:30.933
just like there's poor people
anywhere else.

07:30.967 --> 07:33.625
Kenya is as distinct
and different

07:33.660 --> 07:34.937
from other nations
in Africa

07:34.971 --> 07:37.595
as Texas is
from Mars,

07:37.629 --> 07:40.736
with its own problems and
its own kinds of awesomeness.

07:40.770 --> 07:45.499
It's dynamic, it's changing,
and it's incredible.

07:45.534 --> 07:49.020
Kenya, by Kenyans,
for Kenyans.

07:52.851 --> 07:56.096
But hurdles exist;

07:56.130 --> 07:59.962
bizarre, almost surreal ones,
in this case.

07:59.996 --> 08:02.033
Mitumba,
for instance,

08:02.067 --> 08:05.623
also known as the clothing
of dead white people.

08:05.657 --> 08:08.936
- 70% of Africans are wearing
secondhand clothes.

08:08.971 --> 08:11.629
We can just make
our own clothes

08:11.663 --> 08:13.216
and make them
cheap enough

08:13.251 --> 08:15.011
and make the money
and keep the money.

08:15.046 --> 08:16.772
[upbeat music]

08:16.806 --> 08:18.774
There's also the issue
of dignity.

08:18.808 --> 08:20.085
We have underwear coming in.
We have--

08:20.120 --> 08:21.811
- Underwear?
- Yeah.

08:21.846 --> 08:24.952
- Like poor people like--like
living in Kibera and stuff--

08:24.987 --> 08:26.264
They wear
secondhand underwear.

08:26.298 --> 08:28.093
- It's not cool.
- Well, there's a big market

08:28.128 --> 08:29.957
for that in Japan.

08:29.992 --> 08:31.614
- Oh, but like for
other reasons.

08:31.649 --> 08:33.133
[laughter]

08:33.167 --> 08:36.757
- Njeri Gikera is the owner
of ChilliMango,

08:36.792 --> 08:39.104
and all-Kenyan
street wear company.

08:39.139 --> 08:41.659
Melissa Mbugua is
a managing director

08:41.693 --> 08:43.661
at a creative consulting
firm.

08:45.317 --> 08:46.422
As I understand it,

08:46.456 --> 08:49.149
there used to be 500,000
manufacturing jobs in Kenya,

08:49.183 --> 08:50.944
textile manufacturing,

08:50.978 --> 08:52.808
and there's now
20,000.

08:52.842 --> 08:56.018
- Before the '80s, we had
a booming textile industry...

08:56.052 --> 08:57.157
- Right.
- That could employ

08:57.191 --> 08:59.780
500,000 people,
but now in the '80s,

08:59.815 --> 09:02.783
when the [indistinct]
introduced the free trade,

09:02.818 --> 09:05.061
we got all this--all
the secondhand clothes

09:05.096 --> 09:06.753
coming into
the country.

09:06.787 --> 09:08.824
Before that, they were
actually for charity.

09:08.858 --> 09:10.342
They were meant for
the poor people.

09:10.377 --> 09:12.344
- Here's how
it works.

09:12.379 --> 09:15.140
Your pants or your t-shirt
get old or boring.

09:15.175 --> 09:18.316
So being a good-hearted soul,
rather than throw them out

09:18.350 --> 09:20.352
you drop them in
a charity box

09:20.387 --> 09:23.873
assuming they'll go to someone
who needs them.

09:23.908 --> 09:25.875
But no.

09:25.910 --> 09:28.809
In fact, that charity sells
your pants and your t-shirt

09:28.844 --> 09:30.915
along with a whole lot of
other clothes in bulk

09:30.949 --> 09:33.400
to a secondhand clothing
exporter,

09:33.434 --> 09:37.162
a middle man, part of
a billion-dollar industry.

09:38.854 --> 09:41.304
Exporters then sell your stuff
by the container load

09:41.339 --> 09:43.824
to places
like Kenya.

09:43.859 --> 09:45.274
Along the way,

09:45.308 --> 09:47.932
millions of dollars are
creamed off in duties.

09:47.966 --> 09:52.350
54 million bucks a year
in the port of Mombasa alone.

09:52.384 --> 09:55.284
The old clothes are then
unpacked, sorted,

09:55.318 --> 09:59.806
and sold in markets
throughout the country.

09:59.840 --> 10:03.430
This low-cost clothing option
has absolutely crushed

10:03.464 --> 10:07.054
the domestic
textile market.

10:07.089 --> 10:09.125
Now, some countries in Africa
have said, wait a minute.

10:09.160 --> 10:12.784
This is not good for
our employment situation.

10:12.819 --> 10:14.855
We're not gonna let
this stuff in anymore.

10:14.890 --> 10:16.167
What happened then?

10:16.201 --> 10:19.273
- So then America came
and they told us that

10:19.308 --> 10:21.793
they would have trade sanctions
against us.

10:21.828 --> 10:23.692
- If you didn't take all this..
- Yeah.

10:23.726 --> 10:25.279
- Used clothes.
- Exactly. Exactly, yeah.

10:25.314 --> 10:28.179
'Cause of the free trade
that they--yeah, exactly.

10:28.213 --> 10:29.456
- That's extortion.
- It's pretty much oppressive.

10:29.490 --> 10:30.940
- Yeah,
it's bullying.

10:30.975 --> 10:32.079
- It's real
colonialism.

10:32.114 --> 10:34.150
- USA! USA!
- Yeah.

10:34.185 --> 10:36.325
[laughter]

10:36.359 --> 10:39.052
- So you design
and manufacture?

10:39.086 --> 10:41.813
- Mm-hmm. It's a Kenyan
street wear brand, basically.

10:41.848 --> 10:43.125
So we make hoodies.
We make t-shirts.

10:43.159 --> 10:44.816
- Hoodies?
- Yeah.

10:44.851 --> 10:46.128
- For giants?
Do you make hoodies for giants?

10:46.162 --> 10:48.130
- Yes. Everyone--
everyone's sorted.

10:48.164 --> 10:51.064
- In Oakland where I'm from,
hoodies are kind of a big deal.

10:51.098 --> 10:53.860
So if I was able to go back
with a Kenyan made hoodie,

10:53.894 --> 10:56.000
I'd get a whole Nairobi/Oakland
connection going.

10:56.034 --> 10:57.795
[upbeat music]

10:57.829 --> 11:00.038
- As screwed up as
the whole situation is,

11:00.073 --> 11:03.490
people do love the
availability of cheap clothes.

11:03.524 --> 11:05.492
And Toi Market is
the place to go

11:05.526 --> 11:08.875
for what in New York City
would be called vintage,

11:08.909 --> 11:13.776
a dense labyrinth of shops
neatly organized by specialty.

11:13.811 --> 11:16.261
- Honey, I brought all the UGGs
back from Kenya.

11:16.296 --> 11:18.470
There's gotta be something
in your size.

11:18.505 --> 11:21.059
- The challenge today is gonna
be finding footwear

11:21.094 --> 11:24.304
for Kamau's
decidedly non-Kenyan feet.

11:24.338 --> 11:25.477
Not to mention
mine.

11:25.512 --> 11:28.135
Oh, I need
a half size up.

11:28.170 --> 11:29.792
- Oh, nice.
- Here we go.

11:29.827 --> 11:32.036
I had to come to the continent
to find shoes that fit me.

11:32.070 --> 11:33.106
- High five!
- High ten.

11:33.140 --> 11:34.866
- Great.
- Yeah.

11:34.901 --> 11:36.868
- These are
30-34s?

11:36.903 --> 11:38.870
I'll take these
for sure.

11:38.905 --> 11:41.459
- Let's just be clear. Some
rich, annoying American person

11:41.493 --> 11:42.978
who bought these,
wore them twice.

11:43.012 --> 11:44.807
- Yeah, yeah.
- And then was like,

11:44.842 --> 11:46.188
"Ew, they're out of season."
- Yeah.

11:46.222 --> 11:48.535
- Debbie Harry shirt is
kind of cool.

11:48.569 --> 11:50.951
Yeah.

11:50.986 --> 11:53.505
I will take this
for sure.

11:53.540 --> 11:55.024
- Here we go. Come on.
- Oh, nice.

11:55.059 --> 11:56.129
- Oh, there--
now we're talking.

11:56.163 --> 11:59.028
[funky music]

11:59.063 --> 12:02.031
- Black man in America wearing
a King Kong shirt is not a--

12:02.066 --> 12:03.377
- Oh, yeah, wow.
- Yeah.

12:03.412 --> 12:05.069
I don't know how it goes
over here but in America--

12:05.103 --> 12:06.311
- Turn it down.
- That's a great narc shirt.

12:06.346 --> 12:08.003
- Right.
- That's a great, like,

12:08.037 --> 12:09.901
"Hey, kids."
- Anyone wanna buy some acid?

12:09.936 --> 12:12.145
- This is just weird enough
and simple enough.

12:12.179 --> 12:14.975
- That is
pretty cool.

12:15.010 --> 12:17.184
- I feel like I could,
"Where did you get that shirt?"

12:17.219 --> 12:20.153
"I got it in Kenya."

12:20.187 --> 12:23.432
[upbeat music]

12:23.466 --> 12:26.435
- Is there a solution here?
A mix?

12:26.469 --> 12:29.162
I mean, clearly it's good
for some people.

12:29.196 --> 12:30.819
I mean, I don't have
a lot of money

12:30.853 --> 12:33.166
and I'd like a pretty
fresh-looking pair of Nikes,

12:33.200 --> 12:34.995
this is a good option.
- Yeah.

12:35.030 --> 12:38.999
- I don't think this business
is bad inherently.

12:39.034 --> 12:41.174
I mean, I feel like
these two things seem like

12:41.208 --> 12:42.796
they could exist...
- Together.

12:42.831 --> 12:44.315
- Together, yeah,
you know what I'm saying?

12:44.349 --> 12:45.972
The States, there's like,
you can buy clothes that are

12:46.006 --> 12:47.801
