- ♪ Move it, move it,
move it, yeah ♪

34:09.357 --> 34:11.118
- ♪ Everyone go amok and groovy ♪

34:11.152 --> 34:12.774
- ♪ Move it, move it,
move it, move it ♪

34:12.809 --> 34:16.157
♪

34:35.728 --> 34:39.180
[upbeat rock music]

34:39.215 --> 34:42.908
[majestic music]

34:42.942 --> 34:50.157
♪

34:51.399 --> 34:53.539
- A few hours' drive
from Nairobi,

34:53.574 --> 34:54.851
it's another world.

34:54.885 --> 34:56.922
♪

34:56.956 --> 35:01.202
The Africa of dreams,
of films,

35:01.237 --> 35:02.893
the natural world,

35:02.928 --> 35:05.517
but a world
under constant threat.

35:05.551 --> 35:12.731
♪

35:15.320 --> 35:18.668
Lewa Wildlife Conservancy
seeks to address

35:18.702 --> 35:22.844
the problem of keeping
all this alive and safe

35:22.879 --> 35:26.400
without excluding
or marginalizing the people

35:26.434 --> 35:30.576
who've lived here
for centuries.

35:30.611 --> 35:32.682
That is
a delicate balance.

35:32.716 --> 35:34.580
Man and nature,

35:34.615 --> 35:37.204
how to responsibly care
for one

35:37.238 --> 35:39.240
without negatively impacting
the other

35:39.275 --> 35:41.863
in a world of
ever-decreasing resources.

35:41.898 --> 35:46.903
♪

35:46.937 --> 35:50.182
[upbeat music]

35:50.217 --> 35:52.978
- This is Dave, guys.
Look at this guy here.

35:53.012 --> 35:55.877
This is Dave the Giraffe.
He's a residential giraffe.

35:55.912 --> 35:56.844
- Hi, Dave.

35:56.878 --> 35:58.880
- Our guide is
Karmu Shukiama.

35:58.915 --> 36:00.848
He grew up in
a village near here

36:00.882 --> 36:04.507
and has a deep knowledge of
the wildlife of Lewa.

36:04.541 --> 36:06.198
Are those termite mounds?
- Termite mounds, yeah.

36:06.233 --> 36:08.200
- So that's filled with
termites.

36:08.235 --> 36:09.684
- That's filled with termites.
- That's horrible.

36:09.719 --> 36:11.859
- A little useless trivia,
in a firefight,

36:11.893 --> 36:14.689
you hide behind one of those it
will provide useful cover.

36:14.724 --> 36:16.588
- It's my first safari,
it's a very specific safari

36:16.622 --> 36:19.349
with an expert and with you
with useless information.

36:19.384 --> 36:20.902
- Yes.
- I paid extra for this.

36:20.937 --> 36:25.631
♪

36:25.666 --> 36:27.978
This is significantly better
than the zoo.

36:28.013 --> 36:29.359
I guess that goes
without saying.

36:29.394 --> 36:30.947
- Yeah.

36:30.981 --> 36:32.880
- For some reason,
I don't know if it's just me,

36:32.914 --> 36:36.228
but I had a negative
connotation of safaris.

36:36.263 --> 36:37.781
I mean, I feel like--

36:37.816 --> 36:39.266
- They used to shoot animals
on the safari.

36:39.300 --> 36:40.853
There's our kind
of safari

36:40.888 --> 36:43.235
and then there's the,
you know, Trump Jr. safari.

36:43.270 --> 36:44.857
- Yeah, I think that--I think
I was afraid every time I said

36:44.892 --> 36:46.894
the word that people just,
what are you doing, like--

36:46.928 --> 36:49.690
- No, this is--this is
a good kind of safari.

36:49.724 --> 36:51.347
- Okay, okay, good.
- Good for the world.

36:51.381 --> 36:52.865
- It's 100% good for the world.
- Good for the world.

36:52.900 --> 36:54.729
- So good for
all the communities.

36:54.764 --> 36:57.353
- We need another word
or something.

36:57.387 --> 36:59.769
♪

36:59.803 --> 37:01.426
Are there elephants out here
right now?

37:01.460 --> 37:02.979
- So we have elephants,
yeah.

37:03.013 --> 37:04.463
- Have you ever ridden
on top of an elephant?

37:04.498 --> 37:06.051
- No.
- I have done that,

37:06.085 --> 37:08.916
and you know what's another
interesting little factoid?

37:08.950 --> 37:10.642
- Here we go.

37:10.676 --> 37:12.954
- When you're sitting
on top of an elephant,

37:12.989 --> 37:16.268
the sensation,
the tactile quality,

37:16.303 --> 37:18.788
it's like you're sitting
on top of a giant scrotum.

37:18.822 --> 37:21.791
- Oh, wow. Well,
you're really selling it.

37:21.825 --> 37:24.897
Tony's useless safari facts.
[laughs]

37:24.932 --> 37:30.282
♪

37:30.317 --> 37:32.526
- See an elephant?

37:32.560 --> 37:33.906
Right there.

37:33.941 --> 37:34.942
- Oh!
[laughs]

37:34.976 --> 37:37.910
- Oh, yeah.

37:37.945 --> 37:40.982
♪

37:41.017 --> 37:43.882
Even if you see them in a zoo
closer, they're behind bars.

37:43.916 --> 37:45.435
It just doesn't
feel connected,

37:45.470 --> 37:48.714
but I feel like
we're right here.

37:48.749 --> 37:50.302
- Yeah, he's actually
going someplace.

37:50.337 --> 37:53.409
- Yeah, he's--he's not just
walking in a circle.

37:53.443 --> 37:57.033
He's actually got a--
he's got stuff to do.

37:57.067 --> 38:00.036
[majestic music]

38:00.070 --> 38:04.937
♪

38:04.972 --> 38:07.699
- The fact of the matter is
these magnificent animals

38:07.733 --> 38:09.701
would most likely
be gone

38:09.735 --> 38:12.048
without the intervention
of man.

38:12.082 --> 38:18.365
♪

38:18.399 --> 38:22.058
People pay a lot of money to
come see these animals.

38:22.092 --> 38:24.923
Without that money,
the overwhelming likelihood

38:24.957 --> 38:28.064
is that they would have been
wiped out long ago.

38:28.098 --> 38:30.066
Particularly
this one.

38:30.100 --> 38:32.551
Whoa.
What--what--what--

38:32.586 --> 38:34.001
That's a--

38:34.035 --> 38:37.038
- That's a rhino.
That's our first rhino.

38:37.073 --> 38:40.007
- Wow!

38:40.041 --> 38:43.010
[dramatic music]

38:43.044 --> 38:49.085
♪

38:49.119 --> 38:51.018
- The conservancy was set up
specifically

38:51.052 --> 38:52.882
to protect these guys.

38:52.916 --> 38:56.368
Initially a cattle ranch owned
and operated

38:56.403 --> 38:58.439
by the Craig family,
the Kenyan government,

38:58.474 --> 39:00.890
after finally acknowledging
that the rhinoceros

39:00.924 --> 39:03.479
was on the verge of
extinction, asked the family

39:03.513 --> 39:05.135
to set aside some of
their property

39:05.170 --> 39:08.725
to bring all surviving rhinos
here to recover

39:08.760 --> 39:10.900
and hopefully restore
their numbers.

39:10.934 --> 39:13.903
From only 15 animals
a few years back,

39:13.937 --> 39:17.389
there are over 150 of them
today.

39:17.424 --> 39:20.979
[dramatic music]

39:21.013 --> 39:25.777
♪

39:25.811 --> 39:27.019
[gunshot]

39:27.054 --> 39:29.712
Poaching is, of course,
an ever-present danger

39:29.746 --> 39:31.748
to both the animals
at Lewa

39:31.783 --> 39:33.888
and the people
who look after them.

39:33.923 --> 39:35.890
♪

39:35.925 --> 39:39.791
Particularly the rhinoceros
whose horn is believed

39:39.825 --> 39:42.794
by wealthy Chinese buyers
to be a strong medicine

39:42.828 --> 39:45.452
with virility enhancing
powers.

39:45.486 --> 39:49.076
The reality that the substance
that makes up a rhino horn

39:49.110 --> 39:51.216
is the same as the human
fingernail

39:51.250 --> 39:53.011
does not deter
a market

39:53.045 --> 39:54.771
that will pay tens of
thousands of dollars

39:54.806 --> 39:58.913
for a single horn.

39:58.948 --> 40:00.743
♪

40:00.777 --> 40:02.572
With 62,000 acres
to cover,

40:02.607 --> 40:06.680
Lewa's anti-poaching program
is necessarily aggressive,

40:06.714 --> 40:08.509
inclusive,
and cutting-edge.

40:08.544 --> 40:10.477
relying on
local trackers,

40:10.511 --> 40:12.202
advanced tracking
technologies,

40:12.237 --> 40:15.482
and perhaps most importantly,
good community outreach

40:15.516 --> 40:17.069
and intelligence
gathering.

40:17.104 --> 40:19.900
If the local people are
not on your side,

40:19.934 --> 40:22.558
you are at
a serious disadvantage.

40:22.592 --> 40:24.042
♪

40:26.631 --> 40:28.667
- So that's
a white rhino.

40:28.702 --> 40:30.980
- It's
a white rhino?

40:31.014 --> 40:32.809
- That is a white rhino.
- How do you--

40:32.844 --> 40:34.915
- It has nothing to do with
the coloration.

40:34.949 --> 40:35.985
- Okay.

40:36.019 --> 40:38.608
- White was an Afrikaans name
"wijd"...

40:38.643 --> 40:40.645
- Ah.
- which means wide mouth.

40:40.679 --> 40:42.992
And whoever came to
write about them

40:43.026 --> 40:45.477
[indistinct]
and then they became white.

40:45.512 --> 40:48.100
- You said "white rhino,"
and I was like, ah.

40:48.135 --> 40:48.929
- It's not white.

40:48.963 --> 40:51.587
- I think his dad
might be black.

40:51.621 --> 40:54.555
[upbeat music]

40:54.590 --> 41:01.838
♪

41:06.049 --> 41:08.604
- Does it look like
you wanted it to look?

41:08.638 --> 41:10.088
- [laughs]

41:10.122 --> 41:11.261
- Or expected it
to look?

41:11.296 --> 41:13.919
- I mean--
no.

41:13.954 --> 41:16.301
I mean, I guess
I don't know.

41:16.335 --> 41:18.096
I mean, I grew up as a kid,
you know,

41:18.130 --> 41:20.132
my first images of Africa
were Tarzan, you know.

41:20.167 --> 41:21.996
- Mm-hmm.
- So I don't think I knew

41:22.031 --> 41:24.689
what Kenya, Africa was,
you know?

41:24.723 --> 41:26.760
I mean, I think the expanse of
it is not something...

41:26.794 --> 41:28.520
- Yeah.
- I could be prepared for.

41:28.555 --> 41:31.661
Like, it takes over
the entire horizon.

41:31.696 --> 41:32.973
- What a shithole,
right?

41:33.007 --> 41:34.561
- [laughs]

41:34.595 --> 41:37.840
What a shithole.

41:37.874 --> 41:40.946
I mean, the other thing
I'm aware of too is,

41:40.981 --> 41:42.948
you know, on this trip
is that--

41:42.983 --> 41:46.227
still that thing about like
not wanting to feel like

41:46.262 --> 41:48.920
I have come home,
you know.

41:48.954 --> 41:50.300
- Mm-hmm.
- And yet there is a sense

41:50.335 --> 41:53.925
that there is this
diasporic connection

41:53.959 --> 41:56.962
even though it--I did not
come from Kenya, you know.

41:56.997 --> 41:59.655
It's nice to have
that connection,

41:59.689 --> 42:01.242
even if the frame that the
connection was built through

42:01.277 --> 42:02.761
was colonialism,
you know,

42:02.796 --> 42:04.625
even though that's not,
you know--

42:04.660 --> 42:07.973
But it's--it's the good part
of colonialism.

42:08.008 --> 42:09.147
It brings people
together.

42:09.181 --> 42:12.150
[laughter]

42:12.184 --> 42:14.946
[somber music]

42:14.980 --> 42:18.156
- I don't know, we should kind
of be compulsive reviewing for--

42:18.190 --> 42:19.985
- Yeah.
- Like, if you ever run

42:20.020 --> 42:22.919
for president, you should--you
should be compulsive reviewing.

42:22.954 --> 42:24.956
- At the very least,
I do think that

42:24.990 --> 42:26.336
a lot of perspectives
will be opened up,

42:26.371 --> 42:27.959
a lot of minds
will be changed.

42:27.993 --> 42:29.788
You know, this is on
a very personal note,

42:29.823 --> 42:32.998
like, the idea that
I'm sitting here with you

42:33.033 --> 42:34.034
doing this now

42:34.068 --> 42:37.347
knowing where my life
and career have come,

42:37.382 --> 42:39.108
it's pretty cool.

42:39.142 --> 42:40.350
[laughs]

42:40.385 --> 42:42.111
- That's about as meta
as it gets, right.

42:42.145 --> 42:43.940
- Yeah, no, it's just like
every now and again

42:43.975 --> 42:46.011
I have this, like,
whose life is this?

42:46.046 --> 42:48.773
- I will tell you,

42:48.807 --> 42:51.085
I've got 17
fucking years, okay...

42:51.120 --> 42:52.949
- Yeah.
- and I would--

42:52.984 --> 42:58.092
I--as soon as
the cameras turn off,

42:58.127 --> 43:00.992
and, like, the crew will
be--we'll be sitting around,

43:01.026 --> 43:02.649
we're having
a cocktail,

43:02.683 --> 43:04.064
I fucking pinch
myself,

43:04.098 --> 43:08.413
'cause I cannot fucking believe
that I live to do this...

43:08.447 --> 43:10.242
- I mean, like--
- or see this ever

43:10.277 --> 43:11.416
or that I ever would,

43:11.450 --> 43:15.178
because 44 years old
dunking fries,

43:15.213 --> 43:18.423
I knew with
absolute certainty

43:18.457 --> 43:19.804
that I would never...
- Yeah.

43:19.838 --> 43:23.083
- Ever, ever see Rome,
much less this.

43:23.117 --> 43:25.085
- Yeah.

43:25.119 --> 43:32.333
♪

43:37.822 --> 43:40.825
[upbeat rock music]

43:40.859 --> 43:43.828
[blues music]

43:43.862 --> 43:46.865
♪

43:46.900 --> 43:48.971
- ♪ Hey

43:49.005 --> 43:51.180
- Looking at some of
our cultures,

43:51.214 --> 43:52.975
we know from where
we come from.

43:53.009 --> 43:54.321
Traditionally,
you know,

43:54.355 --> 43:56.806
we've had some sort of
conservation culture.

43:56.841 --> 43:58.187
It sort of got
eroded.

43:58.221 --> 44:00.707
It's been with us,
it's been with our forefathers.

44:00.741 --> 44:02.847
We just lost it
somewhere recently,

44:02.881 --> 44:04.193
and we're trying to
get it back.

44:04.227 --> 44:07.023
♪

44:07.058 --> 44:08.991
- When you have traditional
pastoral communities

44:09.025 --> 44:11.269
under intense
and immediate pressure,

44:11.303 --> 44:13.685
trying to convince them
that wildlife

44:13.720 --> 44:16.308
which can, as in the case of
one rhino or elephant,

44:16.343 --> 44:19.346
bring in life-changing amounts
of money,

44:19.380 --> 44:21.313
it's a hard thing to
convince them

44:21.348 --> 44:24.420
that it is in their long-term
interests to let them live.

44:24.454 --> 44:28.424
Particularly when it was often
wealthy white outsiders

44:28.458 --> 44:30.184
doing the asking.

44:30.219 --> 44:32.462
- If you were very successful in
managing this ex-cattle ranch

44:32.497 --> 44:36.121
as a conservancy, but wildlife
across Kenya as a whole

44:36.156 --> 44:39.124
had no future, then to all
intents and purposes

44:39.159 --> 44:41.955
you just established
a zoo, a large zoo.

44:41.989 --> 44:44.302
And so what Lewa's ethos
has always been

44:44.336 --> 44:46.856
is to show Kenyans that actually
wildlife can have value

44:46.891 --> 44:49.031
and benefit.

44:49.065 --> 44:53.345
[upbeat music]

44:53.380 --> 44:57.108
- Mike Watson is the CEO of
the Lewa Conservancy.

44:57.142 --> 45:00.836
Tom Lalampaa leads
the Northern Rangelands Trust

45:00.870 --> 45:03.528
Faith Riunga is the head
of education at Lewa.

45:03.562 --> 45:07.325
And Wanjiku Kinuthia is
the head of communication.

45:07.359 --> 45:09.016
♪

45:09.051 --> 45:10.949
You're responsible for
a larger picture

45:10.984 --> 45:13.331
involving a huge challenge,
first, the immediate needs

45:13.365 --> 45:15.022
of a lot of people,

45:15.057 --> 45:17.991
but also potential
conflicts with

45:18.025 --> 45:20.096
the traditional
way of life.

45:20.131 --> 45:22.443
How have you been able to do
what you've been able to do?

45:22.478 --> 45:26.516
- I was brought up in a very
strong pastoral background

45:26.551 --> 45:28.311
who really aren't anything
about conservation,

45:28.346 --> 45:32.971
really aren't, because one,
we had the perception

45:33.006 --> 45:35.318
that this is a government thing,
this is about grabbing our land.

45:35.353 --> 45:37.182
- And it probably
doesn't also help

45:37.217 --> 45:39.012
that a lot of that land is
owned by white people, right?

45:39.046 --> 45:40.807
Somebody else is
owning our land.

45:40.841 --> 45:42.291
- Initially.
- Okay.

45:42.325 --> 45:44.534
- That was our perception that
conservation was being driven

45:44.569 --> 45:47.158
by the white, and so it's not
about the communities.

45:47.192 --> 45:50.161
It's not about us,
it's about them.

45:50.195 --> 45:53.336
But you know, gradually,
we came to realize that

45:53.371 --> 45:56.857
the approach that was
being introduced

45:56.892 --> 45:58.341
was a community
approach.

45:58.376 --> 46:02.829
[dramatic music]

46:02.863 --> 46:05.210
- Going back the ten years back,
there was one girl

46:05.245 --> 46:07.109
who made it to
high school.

46:07.143 --> 46:10.526
And she's speaking English,
she's dressing up,

46:10.560 --> 46:13.011
and the other girls are like,
you know what?

46:13.046 --> 46:15.186
I'd like to be her.

46:15.220 --> 46:18.051
And the more and more and more
they've seen

46:18.085 --> 46:21.192
go through high school,
graduate, slowly by slowly,

46:21.226 --> 46:22.572
they get to see the value
themselves.

46:22.607 --> 46:24.160
Education works
very well.

46:24.195 --> 46:26.231
- Are there efforts for
the people in the community

46:26.266 --> 46:28.820
who couldn't afford
to come in here

46:28.855 --> 46:29.994
to sort of see what's
going on in here

46:30.028 --> 46:31.616
so they can have
a further buy-in?

46:31.650 --> 46:34.343
- Yeah. We have a conservation
education program here

46:34.377 --> 46:38.036
where over 3,500 schoolchildren
can come onto Lewa

46:38.071 --> 46:41.212
free of charge, go around,
get to see wildlife.

46:41.246 --> 46:43.317
'Cause you know, unless you can
afford to go to national parks

46:43.352 --> 46:45.147
or--or to places like Lewa...
- Yeah, yeah.

46:45.181 --> 46:47.390
- Then you definitely wouldn't
have the opportunity

46:47.425 --> 46:49.841
to interact with
wildlife.

46:49.876 --> 46:52.844
[upbeat music]

46:52.879 --> 46:57.366
♪

46:57.400 --> 46:59.195
- So we're headed
towards the lions,

46:59.230 --> 47:01.404
is that what we're doing
right now?

47:01.439 --> 47:03.130
♪

47:03.165 --> 47:05.892
- So now you can see at
the peak, you can just see

47:05.926 --> 47:08.032
something sticking there.
That's a lion sitting.

47:08.066 --> 47:10.172
- Oh, yeah, I see,
right next to the little tree.

47:10.206 --> 47:13.520
- Wow.

47:13.554 --> 47:15.453
Whoa.

47:15.487 --> 47:19.008
♪

47:19.043 --> 47:21.528
- Wow, there's
a bunch of them.

47:21.562 --> 47:25.049
- If we're lucky,
they might come down the hill.

47:25.083 --> 47:26.533
- That's lucky?

47:26.567 --> 47:29.018
We define luck
in different ways.

47:29.053 --> 47:34.506
♪

47:34.541 --> 47:37.889
- They seem to be having
their eyes on something.

47:37.924 --> 47:42.998
♪

47:43.032 --> 47:44.482
- Oh! Look, look.

47:44.516 --> 47:46.380
- He's gonna go left,
so we have--

47:46.415 --> 47:48.555
- Oh, jeez, oh!

47:48.589 --> 47:50.212
Hi, how you doing,
lion?

47:50.246 --> 47:55.044
♪

47:55.079 --> 47:57.702
So the lion
is about...

47:57.736 --> 48:00.187
like 30 feet from us
or so.

48:00.222 --> 48:07.229
♪

48:21.968 --> 48:24.211
- Look, look,
look, look.

48:24.246 --> 48:26.213
♪

48:26.248 --> 48:28.043
- My family,
I love you.

48:28.077 --> 48:30.424
That's
just in case.

48:30.459 --> 48:37.535
♪

48:52.239 --> 48:55.035
[upbeat rock music]

48:55.070 --> 48:58.038
[upbeat music]

48:58.073 --> 49:05.287
♪

49:24.616 --> 49:27.136
- Just outside the borders of
Lewa Conservancy

49:27.171 --> 49:32.521
is a Maasai village known as
the Il Ngwesi Community Range.

49:32.555 --> 49:34.385
They're working
with Lewa

49:34.419 --> 49:36.559
to not only embrace
conservation

49:36.594 --> 49:39.666
but also to maintain
their way of life.

49:39.700 --> 49:42.220
- In a very Maasai
traditional way

49:42.255 --> 49:46.569
we've got our diet, which is
meat, blood, and milk.

49:46.604 --> 49:49.227
At least once in a while
they do blood tapping.

49:49.262 --> 49:51.402
♪

49:51.436 --> 49:55.095
- To the Maasai,
the cow is a sacred animal,

49:55.130 --> 49:56.441
giver of
all things.

49:56.476 --> 50:00.652
Unlike the West, meat is not
the primary interest.

50:00.687 --> 50:03.207
Here, cattle are
sustainable,

50:03.241 --> 50:05.071
a long-term asset,

50:05.105 --> 50:08.074
for milk, for cheese,
and on special occasions,

50:08.108 --> 50:09.558
blood

50:09.592 --> 50:11.077
straight from
the tap.

50:11.111 --> 50:13.734
Okay,
here we go.

50:13.769 --> 50:18.049
♪

50:18.084 --> 50:19.050
- Whoa!
- Oh.

50:19.085 --> 50:21.777
- All right,
well done.

50:21.811 --> 50:24.124
- Well done.

50:24.159 --> 50:26.575
- Annoying as hell for the cow,
no doubt,

50:26.609 --> 50:29.060
but decidedly
not fatal.

50:29.095 --> 50:32.581
It might, however, prove fatal
for my colleague Kamau

50:32.615 --> 50:35.204
who, unlike me,
has never experienced

50:35.239 --> 50:37.241
this local
beverage.

50:37.275 --> 50:41.831
A warm jet of arterial blood
into the gourd.

50:41.866 --> 50:45.214
Add some thick, clotting milk,
also from cow,

50:45.249 --> 50:47.561
shake,
and down the hatch.

50:47.596 --> 50:49.184
- Would you like
to have a sip?

50:49.218 --> 50:50.254
- Yes. Sure.
- Perfect.

50:50.288 --> 50:51.393
- Just straight from here?
- Yeah.

50:51.427 --> 50:54.154
- All right,
here we go.

50:54.189 --> 50:57.882
- I can take
the next.

50:57.916 --> 50:59.435
- Are you
gonna try?

50:59.470 --> 51:01.437
- Kamau, you're gonna like it.
It's good.

51:01.472 --> 51:02.749
It's so
delicious.

51:02.783 --> 51:06.132
And keep in mind, the whole
village is watching

51:06.166 --> 51:08.099
and you're
on TV.

51:08.134 --> 51:09.342
- I'm home.
- Yeah.

51:09.376 --> 51:12.172
- [indistinct].

51:12.207 --> 51:14.554
♪

51:14.588 --> 51:15.762
- Makes you
strong.

51:15.796 --> 51:19.593
- Yeah.

51:19.628 --> 51:20.905
Well done.
- Thank you.

51:20.939 --> 51:23.770
Thank you.

51:23.804 --> 51:26.773
[upbeat music]

51:26.807 --> 51:33.780
♪

51:33.814 --> 51:36.231
- Working with the local
Maasai community

51:36.265 --> 51:37.887
is both
an absolute necessity

51:37.922 --> 51:39.579
and the right thing
to do.

51:39.613 --> 51:41.374
To displace and forever
disrupt the people

51:41.408 --> 51:43.445
who've lived here
forever

51:43.479 --> 51:46.275
in favor of animals that
wealthy white people

51:46.310 --> 51:47.863
want to
take pictures of

51:47.897 --> 51:50.245
would be hideous
and unconscionable.

51:50.279 --> 51:51.729
- [speaking native language]
together: Hey.

51:51.763 --> 51:53.903
- [spekaing native language]
together: Hey.

51:53.938 --> 51:56.251
- This is happening elsewhere
on the continent

51:56.285 --> 51:57.942
but the people at Lewa
and Il Ngwesi

51:57.976 --> 52:01.256
are working very hard to
find a better path.

52:01.290 --> 52:02.671
- [speaking native language]
together: Hey.

52:02.705 --> 52:04.259
- [speaking native language]
together: Hey.

52:04.293 --> 52:05.743
- [speaking native language]
together: Hey.

52:05.777 --> 52:06.882
- [speaking native language]
together: Hey.

52:06.916 --> 52:09.264
♪

52:09.298 --> 52:11.749
- [speaking native language]

52:14.821 --> 52:17.375
- He's saying the meaning of
the word Il Ngwesi

52:17.410 --> 52:19.205
is the people who survived,
you know,

52:19.239 --> 52:20.896
by hunting of the government.

52:20.930 --> 52:23.209
- [speaking native language]

52:23.243 --> 52:26.212
- And hunting wasn't what
we understand of hunting today.

52:26.246 --> 52:27.903
It was hunting for survival,
for food,

52:27.937 --> 52:29.870
not for business,
not for selling...

52:29.905 --> 52:31.941
- Trophies.
- Trophies and stuff.

52:31.976 --> 52:35.600
- Jonathan Kip is
a Maassai chief.

52:35.635 --> 52:38.258
Lela Kenyaha is
a Maasai elder here

52:38.293 --> 52:40.260
at Il Ngwesi.

52:40.295 --> 52:43.608
Was this an easy
or a difficult transition

52:43.643 --> 52:46.784
or was it imposed
from outside?

52:46.818 --> 52:50.891
- The transition first is
when the poachers

52:50.926 --> 52:53.204
or the sport hunting
was happening.

52:53.239 --> 52:56.449
We--we think it was
a Western idea...

52:56.483 --> 52:57.760
- Yeah.
- Or Eastern or whatever.

52:57.795 --> 53:00.246
And we were not benefited
a bit

53:00.280 --> 53:03.628
until when an idea
came from Lewa

53:03.663 --> 53:06.631
and said, well, we can--
we can

53:06.666 --> 53:10.773
here in wildlife conservation
for the future of this land,

53:10.808 --> 53:15.295
conserve land, for the future--
future generations.

53:15.330 --> 53:17.470
I think they did what
we said, you know,

53:17.504 --> 53:21.267
teach a person how to fish
instead of providing a fish.

53:21.301 --> 53:22.164
So they taught us
how to fish,

53:22.199 --> 53:23.959
introduced us into
wildlife conservation.

53:23.993 --> 53:27.894
And from there, we are not being
driven by Lewa anymore

53:27.928 --> 53:30.690
or any white person
or any NGO.

53:30.724 --> 53:32.692
Lewa is still a great,
great neighbor.

53:32.726 --> 53:34.521
- Right.
- So we need each other,

53:34.556 --> 53:36.972
but we don't need to--
we're not really dependent

53:37.006 --> 53:39.526
of each other
anymore.

53:39.561 --> 53:41.563
We--we value the game,
we value the animals,

53:41.597 --> 53:43.392
and we know where
we're heading to.

53:43.427 --> 53:46.602
together:
[chanting]

53:53.782 --> 53:56.440
- And just like that,
after months of drought

53:56.474 --> 53:58.787
throughout Kenya,
rain.

53:58.821 --> 54:02.618
- I was told since
I'm Kamau from America,

54:02.653 --> 54:04.275
I brought the rain.
- Right.

54:04.310 --> 54:05.725
- Yeah.
- Well done.

54:05.759 --> 54:07.071
- The bringer of rain.
- Thank you.

54:07.105 --> 54:09.763
- If there was a Maasai--
a Maasai paper,

54:09.798 --> 54:11.869
today would be--
the headline would be--

54:11.903 --> 54:13.042
- Rain.
- Rain.

54:13.077 --> 54:14.768
- Yeah.

54:14.803 --> 54:17.461
together:
[chanting]

54:47.491 --> 54:48.975
- Whoo!

54:49.009 --> 54:51.943
[upbeat music]

54:51.978 --> 54:59.434
♪

55:40.854 --> 55:44.064
[chanting continues]

55:54.972 --> 55:58.113
- Who gets to tell
the stories?

55:58.147 --> 56:01.737
This is a question
asked often.

56:01.772 --> 56:04.982
The answer in this case,
for better or for worse,

56:05.016 --> 56:07.778
is I do,
at least this time out.

56:07.812 --> 56:10.781
[somber music]

56:10.815 --> 56:16.027
♪

56:16.062 --> 56:18.927
I do my best.

56:18.961 --> 56:20.791
I look,
I listen,

56:20.825 --> 56:25.830
but in the end,
I know it's my story.

56:25.865 --> 56:28.799
Not Kamau's,
not Kenya's,

56:28.833 --> 56:31.422
or Kenyans'.

56:31.457 --> 56:34.114
Those stories are yet
to be heard.

56:34.149 --> 56:38.429
♪
